SIMPLE: lubber
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lubber
<hw>Lub"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. dial. Sw.
<ets>lubber</ets>. See <er>Looby</er>, <er>Lob</er>.]</ety> <def>A
heavy, clumsy, or awkward fellow; a sturdy drone; a clown.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lingering <qex>lubbers</qex> lose many a penny.</q>
<rj><qau>Tusser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Land lubber</b></col>, <cd>a name given in contempt by
sailors to a person who lives on land.</cd> -- <col><b>Lubber
grasshopper</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a large, stout, clumsy
grasshopper; esp., <spn>Brachystola magna</spn>, from the Rocky Mountain
plains, and <spn>Romalea microptera</spn>, which is injurious to orange
trees in Florida.</cd> -- <col><b>Lubber's hole</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a hole in the floor of the ⟦ldquo⟧top,⟦rdquo⟧
next the mast, through which sailors may go aloft without going over the
rim by the futtock shrouds. It is considered by seamen as only fit to be
used by lubbers.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Lubber's
line</b></col>, <col><b>Lubber's point</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Lubber's mark</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a line or point in the
compass case indicating the head of the ship, and consequently the
course which the ship is steering.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lubberly</ent>⟦br⟧
